70":"1270","England":"England, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Teyes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Manuel, Luis, Jesus, Pedro, Ruben, Miguel, Roberto, Francisco, Ramon.","Spanish:","plural form of   Rey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Luis, Juan, Alfredo, Roberto, Alfonso, Angel, Eduardo, Jesus, Mariano, Carlos.","Spanish, Galician, and French (Occitan): from Spanish and Old French <i>rey</i> ‘king’ (from Latin <i>rex</i>, genitive <i>regis</i>), which may have denoted someone in the service of a king, or it may have been from the title of someone in a brotherhood or a nickname for someone who behaved in a regal fashion or who had earned the title in some contest of skill or by presiding over festivities. Compare   Del Rey   and Galician   Rei  .","English (Somerset): variant of   Ray  ."]},{"name":"Reyez","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico): altered form of Spanish   Reyes  , influenced by the Spanish patronymic suffix <i>-ez</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Teyes was born in 1238, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1238–":"1238–Surnud","1237–Male":"1237–Surnud","1230–1284":"1230–1284","1270–1325":"1270–1325","1238–Female":"1238–Surnud","1238":"1238","1325":"1325","1237":"1237","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1270":"1270","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1238–":"1238–Kuollut","1237–Male":"1237–Kuoll